
The JS backend owns HIR-to-JavaScript lowering and JS runtime helper emission.

The HTML JS path uses it to build page bundles.
The direct JS backend path can emit a standalone bundle when configured to include every HIR function.

## Main paths

- `src/backends/js/`
- `src/projects/html_project/js_path.rs`
- `src/projects/html_project/external_js/`

## HTML JS page path

The HTML-JS path lowers HIR through the JS backend, then participates in the builder-owned fragment contract: const fragments render into the document, runtime fragment slots are emitted, the generated JS bundle is embedded or module-loaded, active-root `start` is called once, and returned runtime fragments hydrate the slots in source order. The JS lowerer provides the execution artifact: the HTML builder owns the source-order fragment plan.

For page bundles, it emits only the active-root-reachable function set.
It uses the JS backend's referenced external-function metadata to generate only the glue wrappers that the emitted bundle calls.

Reactive runtime fragments are a JS-only concern. Ordinary runtime page-fragment assembly is shared with HTML-Wasm: reactive mounting isn't.

## Direct JS path

The direct JS backend path can emit a complete standalone JS bundle when configured to include every HIR function.

That is a different root policy from the HTML page-bundle path.
Don't accidentally make page bundles include the whole module just because standalone JS can.

## Runtime semantics

Language-owned HIR operations lower through JS runtime helpers or explicit JS code selected by the backend.

Examples include:

- checked numeric operations
- Float formatting
- external Float validation
- runtime casts
- map operations
- string/template runtime construction
- reactive mount/update hooks for supported HTML-JS behaviour

The JS backend must preserve Beanstalk semantics even when JavaScript has different native behaviour.
For example, Float formatting and checked numeric behaviour should not silently fall through to host-native quirks.

## External calls and glue

HIR carries stable external function IDs.
JS lowering records which external functions are referenced by the emitted bundle.
HTML module-level glue generation uses that metadata to emit only the wrappers and imports needed by that route.

The backend should not regenerate imports from source syntax.
The source import surface has already resolved to stable metadata.

## Common mistakes

- Emitting all module functions for a page bundle.
- Generating glue for every registered external function instead of referenced ones.
- Using JavaScript native formatting where Beanstalk requires stable formatting.
- Re-reading source imports instead of HIR external IDs.
- Letting direct JS bundle policy leak into HTML page-bundle policy.

